1lz.title: Bayes's Rule
1lz.clickbait: Bayes's Rule is the core theorem of probability theory saying how to revise our beliefs when we make a new observation.
1lz.text: Bayes's Rule or Bayes's Theorem is the quantitative law governing how to [1ly revise probabilistic beliefs in response to observing new evidence].  Suppose there are two hypotheses being considered, $h_1$ and $h_2$.  Suppose we previously thought that the probability of $h_1$, denoted $\operatorname{P}(h_1)$, was three times as great as $\operatorname{P}(h_2)$ - for example, if $\operatorname{P}(h_1) = 0.6$ and $\operatorname{P}(h_2) = 0.2$, this condition is fulfilled.  Now we see a new piece of evidence, $e_0$.  Suppose the probability of our seeing $e_0$ if $h_1$ is true (denoted by $\operatorname{P}(e_0|h_1)$) is twice as great as the probability of seeing $e_0$ if $h_2$ is true.  Then after executing a Bayesian update on observing $e_0$, we should think that h_1 is now six times as likely as h_2.  To denote the posterior probability of $h_i$ after observing $e_0$, we use $\operatorname{P}(h_i|e_0)$.  Then we obtain: $\frac{\operatorname{P}(h_1|e_0)}{\operatorname{P}(h_2|e_0)} = \frac{\operatorname{P}(h_1)}{\operatorname{P}(h_2)} \cdot \frac{\operatorname{P}(e_0|h_1)}{\operatorname{P}(e_0|h_2)} = 6$.  More generally, Bayes's Rule states that $\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(\mathbf{H}|e) \propto \operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(e|\mathbf{H}) \cdot \operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(\mathbf{H})$.

1lz.clickbait: Bayes's Rule is the core theorem of probability theory saying how to revise our beliefs when we make a new observation.
1lz.text: Bayes's Rule or Bayes's Theorem is the quantitative law governing how to [1ly revise probabilistic beliefs in response to observing new evidence].  Suppose there are two hypotheses being considered, $h_1$ and $h_2$.  Suppose we previously thought that the probability of $h_1$, denoted $\operatorname{P}(h_1)$, was three times as great as $\operatorname{P}(h_2)$ - for example, if $\operatorname{P}(h_1) = 0.6$ and $\operatorname{P}(h_2) = 0.2$, this condition is fulfilled.  Now we see a new piece of evidence, $e_0$.  Suppose the probability of our seeing $e_0$ if $h_1$ is true (denoted by $\operatorname{P}(e_0|h_1)$) is twice as great as the probability of seeing $e_0$ if $h_2$ is true.  Then after executing a Bayesian update on observing $e_0$, we should think that h_1 is now six times as likely as h_2.  To denote the posterior probability of $h_i$ after observing $e_0$, we use $\operatorname{P}(h_i|e_0)$.
